Analyze UK preferences for fridge freezers to optimize product pricing

Yue Wu (270012)

08.02.2023

1 Project introduction

The fridge-freezers market is highly competitive and constantly evolving, with new products and features being introduced regularly. Understanding the preferences and needs of consumers is essential for products to remain competitive and profitable. The aim of this project is to analyze the preferences of consumers in UK for fridge-freezers in order to optimize product pricing.

We will scrape fridge-freezers data from Boots which is a popular home appliance mall in the UK to gather information about consumer preferences, such as their preferred features, brands, and prices. The information will be processed based on R studio and analyzed with statistical methods and visualizations to identify trends and patterns in consumer behavior.

The results of this project will provide valuable information for companies in the fridge-freezer industry, and can be used to inform product development and pricing decisions, helping them stay ahead of the competition and meet the evolving needs of consumers in UK market.

df_data$brand <- stri_trans_toupper(df_data$brand)

As shown in the figure above, the median price of most brands is within 1,000 GBP, the median price of different brands is between 284 and 2069. In addition, there are 72% products in the market whose price is within 1,000 GBP, 19% products are within 1,000-2,000 GBP, and only 9% products exceed 2,000 GBP.

Then we mainly conduct parameter analysis around the parameters that all products have, and Sku is the code of the product and has no reference significance, so we will not analyze it here. And category will be analyzed in combination with other parameters, the analysis results are as follows:

  • Dimensions: In the American fridge freezers category, the height of products is between 177.0-200.0 cm, the width is between 70.0-91.4 cm, and the depth is between 59.0-78.8 cm. In the fridge freezers category, the height of products is between 85.0-118.0 cm, the width is between 48.0-79.6 cm, and the depth is between 49.5-85.1 cm.

  • Total capacity: In the American fridge freezers category, the total capacity of products is between 427-655 liter. In the fridge freezers category, the total capacity of products is between 85-121 liter.

  • Freezer capacity net: In the American fridge freezers category, the net freezer capacity of products is between 107-273 liter. In the fridge freezers category, the height of products is between 99-101 liter.

  • Colour: Among the colors used in all products, the five most commonly used color schemes are white(31.54%), black(15.9%), stainless_steel(13.48%), silver(9.97%), stainless_steel_effect(5.66%).

  • Category: There are two categories of fridge freezers in the UK market, and their proportions are fridge freezers(70.89%), american fridge freezers(29.11%).

  • Country of origin: The products on the market are basically manufactured in other countries, and the proportion of countries producing products from high to low is CHINA(45.55%), TURKIYE(17.25%), POLAND(13.75%), ITALY(7.28%), GERMANY(6.74%), BULGARIA(3.5%), ROMANIA(2.96%), SOUTH KOREA(1.89%), SERBIA(0.54%), THAILAND(0.54%).

  • Energy rating: The energy rating distribution of the product ranges from high to low: F(61.73%), E(23.99%), D(10.78%), C(2.43%), A(0.54%), A+(0.27%), B(0.27%).

  • Frost free freezer: For this function parameter, whether the product has this parameter distribution is as follows: yes(73.32%), no(26.42%), automatic(0.27%).

  • Manufacturer warranty: The manufacturers warranty year proportion for the product from highest to lowest is 2(58.49%), 1(29.92%), 5(11.59%) year.

2.3.4 Rating analysis

  • This project selects target data is around the preference of UK customers for fridge-freezers, we combine customer ratings and the number of reviews as important fundamental metrics.
  • The scoring system of this shopping website is based on the fact that sellers will automatically give five points of praise if they do not post a comment, so we can simply seem the number of reviews as the number of purchased items(sales).
  • We has filtered products with rating in the pre-processing stage.
cor11 <- round(cor(df_data$rating, df_data$review_amount),2)
rate_data <- df_data$rating %>% table() %>% data.frame() 
names(rate_data) <- c("rate","freq")
rate_data <- rate_data %>% mutate(percent = stri_paste(round(freq / sum(freq)*100,2),'%') ) 
rate_data %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = rate, y = freq)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  xlab("Rating") +
  ylab("Rating freq") +
  ggtitle("Rating Distribution") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, vjust = 1)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = percent, y = freq+1))

As shown in the figure above, most products have a rating of 4.4 or higher, and products with a rating of 4.8 account for the highest proportion. Moreover, after conducting a correlation test between rating and number of rating to each product, the correlation coefficient is 0.08, we can find that there is almost no correlation between them.

sc1 <-price_rate %>% ggplot(aes(x = rate, y = price)) +

  ggtitle("Relationship Between Rating and Price") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, vjust = 1))
sc2 <- price_rate %>% ggplot(aes(x = number, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Sale") +
  ylab("Price(GBP)") +
  ggtitle("Relationship Between Sale and Price") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, vjust = 1))
grid.arrange(sc1, sc2, ncol = 2)

As shown in the figure above, rating seems to have no correlation with price, and the ratings of most products are between 4-5. In addition, there is a weak negative correlation between sale and price. The price of the products with the higher sales is concentrated within 1,000 GBP, followed by 1,000-2,000 GBP. As the price continues to rise, sale becomes very low. This may be related to the price-friendly positioning of the sites we crawl. In addition, the correlation coefficients of price, rating and sales are respectively:0.08 and -0.19, which is consistent with the trend of our previous analysis.

3 Project conclusion

  1. By studying the sales of different products, the more insured strategy is that the median of the main products should be controlled between 500 - 1000 GBP, and the price of high-end products should be 1000 - 2500 GBP.
  2. By increasing the market share of product quantity, it can increase sales and customer recognition to a certain extent.
  3. The company can configure products according to the high-frequency attributes that appear in the market to launch more products that meet market demand.
